#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "IP address unban"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Fail2Ban** is an intrusion prevention software that protects computer servers against brute-force attacks. It monitors certain logs and will ban IP addresses that show brute-force-like behavior.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:8
msgid ""
"In particular, **Fail2Ban** monitors `SSH` connection attempts. After 5 "
"failed SSH connection attempts, Fail2Ban will ban the IP address from "
"connecting via SSH for 10 minutes. If this address fails several times, it "
"might get banned for a week."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "Unban an IP address"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:12
msgid ""
"To unblock an IP address, you must first access your server by some means "
"(for example from another IP address or from another internet connection "
"than the banned one)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:14
msgid ""
"Then, look at the **Fail2Ban’s log** to identify in which `jail` the IP "
"address has been banned:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:15
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sudo tail /var/log/fail2ban.log\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:47 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: INFO    [sshd] Found 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:49 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: INFO    [sshd] Found 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:51 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: INFO    [sshd] Found 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:54 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: INFO    [sshd] Found 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:57 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: INFO    [sshd] Found 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:57 fail2ban.actions [1837]: NOTICE  [sshd] Ban 11.22.33.44\n"
"2019-01-07 16:24:57 fail2ban.filter  [1837]: NOTICE  [recidive] Ban 11.22.33.44\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:27
msgid ""
"Here, the `11.22.33.44` IP address has been banned in the `sshd` and "
"`recidive` jails."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:29
msgid "Then deban the IP address with the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sudo fail2ban-client set sshd unbanip 11.22.33.44\n"
"sudo fail2ban-client set recidive unbanip 11.22.33.44\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Whitelist an IP address"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:38
msgid ""
"If you don’t want a \"legitimate\" IP address to be blocked by **YunoHost** "
"anymore, then you have to fill it in the whitelist of the `jail` "
"configuration file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:40
msgid ""
"When updating the **Fail2Ban** software, the original `/etc/fail2ban/"
"jail.conf` file is overwritten. So it is on a new dedicated file that we "
"will store the changes. They will thus be preserved over time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:42
msgid ""
"Start by creating the new jail configuration file which will be called "
"`yunohost-whitelist.conf`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:46
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    sudo touch /etc/fail2ban/jail.d/yunohost-whitelist.conf\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:48
msgid "Edit this new file with your favorite editor:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:52
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    sudo nano /etc/fail2ban/jail.d/yunohost-whitelist.conf\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:54
msgid ""
"Paste the following content into the file and adapt the IP address "
"`XXX.XXX.XXX.XXX`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:57
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    [DEFAULT]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:60
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ignoreip = 127.0.0.1/8 XXX.XXX.XXX.XXX #<= the IP address (you can put more than one, separated by a space) that you want to whitelist\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:62
msgid "Save the file and reload the Fail2Ban configuration:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:66
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    sudo fail2ban-client reload\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/50.troubleshooting/05.fail2ban.mdx:67
msgid ""
"Congratulations, no more risks of banning yourself from your own YunoHost "
"server!"
msgstr ""
